content.description: Start standing with sidepulls on either side of the arete in the corridor at head height.  Climb the arete avoiding the dab factor.
content.protection: Pad and maybe don’t fall at the top.
content.location: At the head of the short corridor on the right (north) side of the World War Z Boulder.

content.description: Worth seeking out, start sitting with obvious big ledge for your hands.  Trend left through the overhanging face via prominent ledges and mantle with a juggy undercling probably helping a lot.
content.protection: 3/4 pads and a spot.  The landing isn’t perfect.
content.location: Locate the main Clusterf—— Boulders.  This is on the same level of the hillside and 100 feet south.  It faces downhill.

content.description: SDS high on two compressing rails and climb straight up the short overhanging block.

A cool boulder worth checking out.. especially if you’re in the area.Start sitting with an obvious undercling feature.  Climb up the overhanging face, likely using a couple of awesome slopers and top out on better holds.
content.location: From World War Z Boulder.. cut south along a cliff band that is just up hill then into the talus.  At about the same level on the hillside.  200 feet away and the boulder faces downhill.  200 feet or less down from the 45 boulder if you are familiar with that.

content.description: Start as for World War Z but instead of traversing up and to the left, continue straight up the boulder over an intimidating landing and a tricky lip encounter. Once fully on the slab, the climb eases up significantly, but it is a no fall situation...
Start sitting right of World War Z, left hand in a flexy undercling that is seemingly solid and right out on a pinch.  Move up and right through the face and top out on the arete to the right.
content.protection: Pads, be wary of the slab behind you throughout the climb.
content.location: On the World War Z boulder.

content.description: A nice block with a chunky east face, reminiscent of Mean Gurlz.
